ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='The tests are failing because of how `expectLater` and `await` intera
ct with Cubit streams. The problem is:\n\n1. `expectLater(cubit.stream, emitsInO
rder(...))` starts listening to the stream\n2. `await cubit.fetchMatches()` runs
, which emits states synchronously\n3. But `expectLater` is awaited BEFORE `fetc
hMatches()`, so the listener is set up before the states are emitted\n\nWait, th
at should work. Let me think again...\n\nActually, looking at the error:\n```\nE
xpected: should do the following in order:\n          • emit an event that Match
ListLoadInProgress:<MatchListLoadInProgress()>\n          • emit an event that <
Instance of \'MatchListLoadFailure\'> with `message`: \'请先完善个人资料\'\nActu
al: <Instance of \'_BroadcastStream<MatchListState>\'>\n Which: emitted x Stream
closed.\n          which didn\'t emit an event that MatchListLoadInProgress:<Mat
chListLoadInProgress()>\n```\n\nThis means `expectLater` started listening, but 
the stream closed without emitting `LoadInProgress`. Why? Because `cubit.fetchMa
tches()` was called in a PREVIOUS test, and the cubit was closed in `tearDown`. 
But wait, each test has its own `setUp` which creates a new cubit.\n\nWait, the 
error is for the "profile incomplete" test. Let me trace:\n1. `setUp` creates ne
w cubit and repository\n2. `expectLater` is set up\n3. `await cubit.fetchMatches
()` is called\n\nBut `expectLater` is awaited FIRST, then `fetchMatches`. That m
eans:\n1. `await expectLater(...)` - this waits for the stream to emit the expec
ted states. But `fetchMatches` hasn\'t been called yet, so no states are emitted
. The stream is idle.\n2. Since no states are emitted, `expectLater` waits... an
d waits... until timeout.\n\nOH! I see the bug! In my code:\n```dart\nawait expe
ctLater(cubit.stream, emitsInOrder(expectedStates));\nawait cubit.fetchMatches()
;\n```\n\nI\'m awaiting `expectLater` BEFORE calling `fetchMatches`! `expectLate
r` waits for the stream to emit the expected events, but since `fetchMatches` ha
sn\'t been called yet, no events are emitted. So it times out!\n\nIn the origina
l matching_bloc_test.dart, they do:\n```dart\nbloc.add(const RecommendationsRequ
ested());\nawait expectLater(bloc.stream, emitsInOrder([...]));\n```\n\nThey tri
gger the event FIRST, then await the stream. This works because Bloc processes e
vents asynchronously, so the event is queued and the stream listener is set up b
efore the states are emitted.\n\nBut for Cubit, `fetchMatches` is a method that 
emits states synchronously. So:\n- If I call `fetchMatches()` first, the states 
are emitted immediately, before `expectLater` starts listening.\n- If I call `ex
pectLater` first, it waits forever because `fetchMatches` hasn\'t been called.\n
\nFor Cubit, the correct pattern is different. I need to either:\n1. Use `unawai
ted(cubit.fetchMatches())` and then `await expectLater(...)`\n2. Or set up `expe
ctLater` but not await it, then call `fetchMatches()`, then await the `expectLat
er` Future\n\nLet me look at how other Cubit tests in the project handle this...
',
